## Shipped-surface review (post-mortem factoryskills-5og)

The bead's prose mentions symbols that drifted from `main`. Adjusted:

- The trajectory writer is `TrajectoryWriter` (not `TurnWriter`).
  `LoopDriver` already owns it and writes turns, `PluginDisabledEvent`,
  and `SessionFooter`. The host has no writer-facing surface.
- `exploration_agent` does not depend on `exploration_flutter`, so
  `PluginRegistry.mergedTools()` is unreachable from the harness. The
  harness-side "plugin manifest" is the `List<PluginManifestEntry>` on
  `ExplorationSession.handshake.plugins`. That entry only carries
  pre-namespaced tool *names*; full `ToolDescriptor`s (with
  `inputSchema`) are caller-supplied (cx6.20 CLI / cx6.21 DevTools).
- `LoopDriver` already owns `pluginFailureTracker` and writes
  `PluginDisabledEvent`. The host's `disablePlugin` only updates local
  active-set bookkeeping and delegates to
  `ExplorationSession.disablePlugin` (so `PluginAutoDisabled` reaches
  the progress stream). No second tracker, no second writer call.
- `ExplorationSession._client` and `_puller` are private. We add two
  `@internal` accessors so the host can reach the transport.
- Plugin-side notify (`onActionExecutedAll`) runs *inside* the target
  app inside the binding's `executeAction` handler. The harness
  `notifyPlugins` is a no-op; doubling it would dispatch twice.

