### 3. Tighten swift-infer's catch site — `packages/exploration_devtools/lib/src/panels/model_catalog.dart:162-201`

Today `_fetchSwiftInfer` catches `on Object` after `_client.get`, which silently swallows 401/403 *and* `ClientException`. We keep the existing 404/5xx → fallback semantics (the gateway-doesn't-implement-/v1/models case), but stop swallowing 4xx-other-than-404 and stop swallowing `ClientException`. The classifier still wraps both into typed `ModelCatalogError`:

```dart
Future<List<ResolvedModel>> _fetchSwiftInfer(
  SwiftInferUiConfig cfg,
  String conversationId,
) async {
  final uri = _modelsUri(cfg);
  final http.Response res;
  try {
    res = await _client.get(uri, headers: cfg.headersFor(conversationId));
  } on http.ClientException catch (e) {
    throw ModelCatalogError(
      kind: ModelCatalogErrorKind.networkOrCors,
      message: e.message,
      targetUrl: uri,
    );
  }
  if (res.statusCode == 404 || res.statusCode >= 500) {
    return _swiftInferFallback(cfg);
  }
  if (res.statusCode >= 400) {
    throw ModelCatalogError(
      kind: ModelCatalogErrorKind.httpError,
      statusCode: res.statusCode,
      message: 'HTTP ${res.statusCode}',
      targetUrl: uri,
    );
  }
  final Map<String, dynamic> decoded;
  try {
    decoded = (jsonDecode(res.body) as Map).cast<String, dynamic>();
  } on FormatException {
    // Malformed JSON from a swift-infer gateway is treated the same as
    // "doesn't implement /v1/models": fall back to the configured
    // default model id so the user can still pick something.
    return _swiftInferFallback(cfg);
  }
  final data = (decoded['data'] as List?) ?? const [];
  if (data.isEmpty) return _swiftInferFallback(cfg);
  return data
      .whereType<Map<dynamic, dynamic>>()
      .map((m) => m.cast<String, dynamic>())
      .map((m) {
    final id = m['id'] as String;
    return ResolvedModel(
      id: id,
      label: (m['display_name'] as String?) ?? id,
      capabilities: capabilitiesFor('swift-infer', id),
    );
  }).toList();
}
```

Behavior delta vs today: `ClientException` (CORS / connection refused) NO LONGER falls back silently — it raises a typed `ModelCatalogError` so the banner fires. 404 / 5xx / malformed JSON / empty data continue to fall back (existing semantics — these match "gateway doesn't implement /v1/models", which is a legitimate runtime mode rather than a misconfiguration).

